{"add":{"doc":{"id":"a9c99fc8524a22ab38618007b3d7174690f041fa47783c135bb873cdfb3f784f","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b9/Aghlabids_Dynasty_800_-_909_%28AD%29.svg/220px-Aghlabids_Dynasty_800_-_909_%28AD%29.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["It was during this chaotic era that Italy saw the rise of a peculiar institution, the medieval commune. Given the power vacuum caused by extreme territorial fragmentation and the struggle between the Empire and the Holy See, local communities sought autonomous ways to restore law and order.[42] In 1176 a league of city-states, the Lombard League, defeated the German emperor Frederick Barbarossa at the Battle of Legnano, thus ensuring effective independence for most of northern and central Italian cities. In coastal and southern areas, the maritime republics, the most notable being Venice, Genoa, Pisa and Amalfi, heavily involved in the Crusades, grew to eventually dominate the Mediterranean and monopolise trade routes to the Orient.[43]"]}}}